{"title_page": "2-Tone Entertainment", "text_new": "{{Proposed deletion/dated\n  |concern = Blatantly promotional article, substantially written by SPAs. Refbombed, but almost none of the refs are RSes actually about the company. [[WP:BEFORE]] doesn't show much better.\n  |timestamp = 20200331201922\n  |help = off\n}}\n{{advert|date=March 2020}}\n{{puffery|date=March 2020}}\n{{notability|corp|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = 2-Tone Entertainment\n| logo = 2-Tone_Entertainment_Logo_2014.png\n| type = [[Private ownership]],<br>[[Private company]]\n| foundation = 2004\n| founder = Shaurav D'Silva\n| location_city = [[London]]\n| location_country = United Kingdom\n| genre = [[Dance Music]], [[Hip hop music|Hip-hop]], [[Alternative hip hop]], [[R&B]], [[Drum & Bass]], [[Grime (music)|Grime]]\n| area_served = [[United Kingdom]]<br>[[European Union]]\n| key_people = Shaurav D'Silva<br/> <small> (CEO)</small>\n| industry = [[Music industry]],<br> [[Record Label]] <br> [[A&R]] & [[Artist Management]]\n| products = [[Record Label]] <br> [[Publishing]]<br> [[Artist Management]]\n| homepage = {{url|http://www.2tone-entertainment.com}}\n}}\n'''2-Tone Entertainment (also known as 2TE)''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] based [[independent record label|independent Record Label]] who also specialise in Music Publishing and Talent Management.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://futuremusicforum.com/artist-talk|title=Future Music Forum|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=2-Tone Entertainment|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> The company was founded by Shaurav D'Silva in 2004.\n \n[[2-Tone Entertainment]] have worked with various [[Major Label|major label]] partners including [[Warner Music Group]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/shaurav-dsilva-launches-new-label-warner-bros-records-uk/|title=Shaurav D'Silva launches new imprint with Warner Bros Records UK|date=2016-09-08|website=Music Business Worldwide|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>, [[3 Beat Records]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/d-silva-keeps-the-beat_17682951|title=Jamaica Observer Limited|website=Jamaica Observer|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> & the [[Universal Music Group]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amsterdam-dance-event.nl/en/artists-speakers/shaurav-dsilva/9930/|title=Shaurav D'Silva|website=ADE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> since 2011, successfully launching the careers of a number of artists including [[Rudimental]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amsterdam-dance-event.nl/en/artists-speakers/shaurav-dsilva/9930/|title=Shaurav D'Silva|website=ADE|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>, [[Sigma (group)|Sigma (group]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=302844&title+-WARNER-U.K.-FORMS-DANCE-LABEL-|title=HITS Daily Double : Rumor Mill - WARNER U.K. FORMS DANCE LABEL|website=HITS Daily Double|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>[[Sigma (group)|)]], Fuse [[Fuse ODG|ODG]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://urbandevelopment.co.uk/blog/meet-the-speakers-for-getting-7306|title=UD|website=urbandevelopment.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> ,[[Taio Cruz]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/taio-cruz-interview-ive-never-been-a-spotlight-kind-of-person-a3732951.html|title=Taio Cruz speaks about shying away from the spotlight|date=2018-01-05|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> and Saweetie<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/tastemakers/read/on-the-radar-saweetie/072589|title=On The Radar: Saweetie|website=www.musicweek.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> .\n\n[[2-Tone Entertainment|2-Tone Entertainment's]] management and publishing roster also represent a number of writers, producers and artists including [[Diztortion]], Alastair O'Donnell (AoD), [[Eyelar]] and [[Ts7|TS7]]. They have also consulted for a number of urban entertainment and lifestyle brands such as [[SBTV]] and [[MOBO]].\n\nOn September 8, 2016, [[Warner Music]] announced the launch of new record label imprint in conjunction with [[2-Tone Entertainment]] called 2TE Records. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicweek.com/labels/read/shaurav-d-silva-to-head-up-new-warner-imprint-2te-records/065901|title=Shaurav D'Silva to head up new Warner imprint 2TE Records|website=Musicweek.com}}</ref>\n\n==2004-2011==\nThe company was founded by Shaurav D'Silva in 2004. His background as a [[UK garage|UK Garage]] DJ and club promoter <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/D-Silva-keeps-the-BEAT_17682951 |title=D'Silva keeps the BEAT - Entertainment |website=JamaicaObserver.com |date=2014-10-05 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> led to him becoming a consultant on a range of urban and dance music related events and projects including the [[Urban Music Awards]] Ceremony,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=15599&sectioncode=1 |title=In The City panel details announced |publisher=Music Week |date=2005-09-23 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> where he brokered deals with lifestyle brands and record companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://urbanmusicawards.net/2011/08/past-winners-2004/ |title=Past winners 2004 |publisher=Urban Music Awards |date= |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> The company also began to work as consultants with artists and record labels in tastemaker A&R, Promotion and PR. In 2010 [[2-Tone Entertainment]] client [[DJ Cameo]] released a compilation via [[Ministry of Sound]] Recordings called \"Ayia Napa Reunion 2010\"- it was a mixture of [[UK garage|UK Garage]], [[Funky house|Funky House]] and Commercial Club Tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/ayia-napa-reunion-2010-mixed/id396783049 |title=iTunes - Music - Ayia Napa Reunion 2010 (Mixed by DJ Cameo) by DJ Cameo |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2010-10-10 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ministryofsound.com/shop/product/music/28717/dj-cameo-presents-ayia-napa-reunion-2010/ |title=DJ Cameo Presents Ayia Napa Reunion 2010 |publisher=Ministry of Sound |date=2010-10-10 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> It was accompanied by an online documentary on [[Ayia Napa]] and club culture. A UK tour with [[BBC Radio 1Xtra|BBC 1Xtra]] DJ- [[DJ Cameo]] and [[Paradigm Talent Agency|Coda Talent]] agency followed.\n\n==2011-2012==\n2011 saw [[2-Tone Entertainment]] venture into [[music publisher (popular music)|music publishing]]. Focusing on the development of writers and producers, the company signed female rapper [[Baby Blue (rapper)|Baby Blue]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.district6.co.uk/index.php?page=writers&id=1064 |title=Baby Blue &#124; District 6 &#124; Music Publishing |publisher=District 6 |date= |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> and production outfit [[Rudimental]] through a joint venture with independent [[music publisher (popular music)|music publisher]] District 6 .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.district6.co.uk/index.php?page=writers&id=1079 |title=Piers Agget (Rudimental) &#124; District 6 &#124; Music Publishing |publisher=District 6 |date= |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref>\n\nThe company also begun representing Singer and Film and TV Actress [[Preeya Kalidas]], who released a number of tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01d0jr6 |title=BBC Radio 1 - Nihal, Preeya Kalidas, DaVinche & TazZz All Live On The Show |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2012-03-14 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> Preeya won best female at the Asian Music Awards the same year following her success with the chart single \"[[Cross My Heart (Skepta song)|Cross My Heart]]\" with [[Skepta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=1044557&sectioncode=1 |title=Jay Sean and Preeya Kalidas win at UK Asian Music Awards |publisher=Music Week |date=2011-03-14 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/cross-my-heart-ft.-preeya/id394940012 |title=iTunes - Music - Cross My Heart (ft. Preeya Kalidas) by Skepta |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2010-10-17 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, [[2-Tone Entertainment]] officially begun its relationship with [[3 Beat Records|3Beat Records]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicweek.com/labels/read/shaurav-d-silva-to-head-up-new-warner-imprint-2te-records/065901|title=Shaurav D'Silva to head up new Warner imprint 2TE Records|website=www.musicweek.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>, a Liverpool Based record label who's roster included artists [[Skepta]], [[Sway (rapper)|Sway]] and [[Matrix & Futurebound]] as part of a joint venture with [[Universal Music Group|Universal Records]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/3-beat-renews-joint-venture-universal-music-uk/|title=3 Beat renews joint venture with Universal Music UK|date=2018-02-15|website=Music Business Worldwide|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>. \n\nIn December 2011, [[2-Tone Entertainment]] organised and promoted the 1st annual [[SB.TV|SBTV]] Christmas party, with artists including: [[Labrinth]], [[Devlin (rapper)|Devlin]], [[Rizzle Kicks]], [[Tinchy Stryder]], [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]], [[Misha B]], [[Cher Lloyd]], [[Maxsta]], [[Dot Rotten]] and many others.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matilda Egere-Cooper |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/sbtv-xmas-party-koko-london-6280485.html |title=SB.TV Xmas party, Koko, London - Reviews - Music |publisher=The Independent |date=2011-12-22 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref> \n\n==2012-2013==\nIn February 2012, it was announced that [[2-Tone Entertainment]] would be producing and event managing the annual [[MOBO Awards|Mobo]] Tour, in particular the [[MOBO]] Industry takeover even- a talent showcase for new talent from the Liverpool region.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.connexionslive.com/Libraries/Parent_Carers_Documents/MOBO_Tour_2012_-_Liverpool.sflb.ashx |title=The MOBO Tour 2012 |website=Connexionslive.com |accessdate=2014-07-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140311062406/http://www.connexionslive.com/Libraries/Parent_Carers_Documents/MOBO_Tour_2012_-_Liverpool.sflb.ashx |archive-date=2014-03-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\n2012 was also the year that UK production outfit [[Rudimental]] had their breakthrough hit \"[[Feel the Love (Rudimental song)|Feel the Love]]\", which was recorded during their term as management &publishing clients with [[2-Tone Entertainment]]. The record went on to sell over 1 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20120603/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 &#124; Official Charts Company|website=Officialcharts.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, new [[3 Beat Records|3Beat Records]] signing [[Stylo G]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/rachelwhitepr/view/68552/ |title=Stylo G unveils first single on 3 Beat Records - 'Soundbwoy' |publisher=Pressparty |date= |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref> had chart success with his debut single on the label with \"[[Soundbwoy]]\". The track entered the chart at number 18 on the OCC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2013-06-08/ |title=2013-06-08 Top 40 Official Singles Chart UK Archive |publisher=Official Charts |date=2013-06-08 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref> The track was produced by Dutch born producer [[Diztortion]] who had recently joined the [[2-Tone Entertainment]] Talent Management roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Sweet-sound-of-Diztortion_17544861|title=Sweet sound of Diztortion - Entertainment|first=Jamaica Observer|last=Limited|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe success with [[Stylo G]] was quickly followed by the success of another signing [[Fuse ODG]] with his popular club anthem \"[[Antenna (song)|Antenna]]\" which entered the UK Chart at Number 7 and went on to become a 200,000 plus selling, silver certified record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2013-06-15/ |title=2013-06-15 Top 40 Official Singles Chart UK Archive |publisher=Official Charts |date=2013-06-15 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref> [[Fuse ODG]] followed \"[[Antenna (song)|Antenna]]\" with \"[[Azonto (Fuse ODG song)|Azonto]]\", a popular dance that was created in [[Ghana]]. The record reached number 29 in the UK OCC Charts <ref>{{Citation|title=Fuse ODG|date=2020-03-25|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Fuse_ODG&oldid=947355878|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.\n\nThe [[MOBO Awards]] recognised the successes of both [[Stylo G]] and [[Fuse ODG]] with 5 nominations at the 2013 Awards. [[Fuse ODG]] went on to win \"Best African Act\".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/interview-mobo-nominee-and-confirmed-artist-afrobeats-superstar-fuse-odg |title=Interview: Mobo Nominee Afrobeats Superstar Fuse Odg &#124; Mobo Awards |publisher=Mobo.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/winner-best-african-act-fuse-odg-wows-mobo-fans-million-pound-girl |title=Winner Of 'Best African Act' Fuse ODG Wows MOBO Fans With 'Million Po &#124; MOBO Awards |publisher=Mobo.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Shaurav also signed drum & bass duo [[Sigma (group)|Sigma]] to [[3Beat Records]]. The first official release was \"[[Rudeboy (Sigma song)|Rudeboy]]\" - the track was B-listed on BBC Radio 1 and reached number 56 in the OCC chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/rudeboy-feat.-doctor-single/id742129844 |title=iTunes - Music - Rudeboy (feat. Doctor) - Single by Sigma |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2013-12-15 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==2014-2015==\n2014 saw continued chart success with top 10 chart singles for [[Fuse ODG]] with \"[[Million Pound Girl (Badder Than Bad)]]\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Fuse ODG|date=2020-03-25|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Fuse_ODG&oldid=947355878|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> and [[Matrix & Futurebound]] with \"[[Control (Matrix & Futurebound song)|Control]]\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/18431/matrix-and-futurebound/|title=FUTUREBOUND & MATRIX {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.\n\nIn April 2014, [[2-Tone Entertainment]] and [[3 Beat Records|3Beat Records]] celebrated an [[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]] (OCC) UK Number 1 with [[Sigma (group)]] [[Nobody to Love]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lane |first=Dan |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sigma-score-debut-number-1-single-with-nobody-to-love-2920/ |title=Sigma score debut Number 1 single with Nobody To Love |website=Officialcharts.com |date=2014-04-13 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> The track went on to become a number 1 across 8 countries worldwide and is certified platinum in the UK and New Zealand <ref>[[Nobody to Love]]</ref>\n\n[[Fuse ODG]] followed up his success on \"[[Million Pound Girl (Badder Than Bad)]]\" with a collaboration with Dancehall superstar Sean Paul called \"Dangerous Love\" - this went on to be Fuse's biggest selling solo single (over 400,000 units) and reached UK Number 3 in the UK OCC Charts<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/26103/fuse-odg/|title=Fuse ODG {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.\n\n[[Sigma (group)|Sigma]] also released \"[[Changing (Sigma song)|Changing]]\" featuring vocalist Paloma Faith. The record was an instant success and became the band's second Platinum selling Number 1 record in 2014- it was the 1st time an Electronic artist had achieved back to back UK No 1 Records.<ref>{{cite web|last=Copsey |first=Rob |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sigma-land-second-number-1-single-this-year-with-changing-ft-paloma-faith3140/ |title=Sigma land second Number 1 single this year with Changing FT Paloma Faith |website=Officialcharts.com |date=2014-09-21 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==2015-2016==\nIn 2015, [[2-Tone Entertainment|2-Tone Entertainment's]] management client [[Diztortion]] registered further chart success with the track [[Fester Skank]] which he produced and collaborated on with UK Grime Artist [[Lethal Bizzle]]. The track peaked at Number 11 on the OCC Charts and has since achieved Gold sales status<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/fester-skank/|title=fester skank {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.\n\nFollowing the sustained success with [[Sigma (group)|Sigma]] and [[Fuse ODG]], Shaurav D'Silva was nominated for A&R Award Of The Year at the [[Music Week]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweekawards.com/finalists/|title=Home: Music Week Awards 2017|website=Musicweekawards.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Sigma (group)|Sigma]] were also nominee for 2 X [[Brit Awards]] - for Best Video and for Best Single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brits.co.uk/news/british-single-nominations-announced|title=British Single nominations announced|website=Brits.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==2017-2020==\n[[2-Tone Entertainment]] announced its new label venture 2TE Records with [[Warner Music]] in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/shaurav-dsilva-launches-new-label-warner-bros-records-uk/|title=Shaurav D'Silva launches new imprint with Warner Bros Records UK|date=September 8, 2016|website=Musicbusinessworldwide.com}}</ref> \n\nThe venture saw the label sign a number of artists including US Rapper [[Saweetie]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/tastemakers/read/on-the-radar-saweetie/072589|title=On The Radar: Saweetie|website=www.musicweek.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> , [[Taio Cruz]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/taio-cruz-interview-ive-never-been-a-spotlight-kind-of-person-a3732951.html|title=Taio Cruz speaks about shying away from the spotlight|date=2018-01-05|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> , [[Fuse ODG]] , and [[Disc jockey|Dj]]/ producers Conducta, and Crazy Cousinz. Most notable releases under the deal included [[Fuse ODG]] collaboration with [[Ed Sheeran]] - [[Boa Me]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52611/fuse-odg-ed-sheeran-mugeez/|title=FUSE ODG/ED SHEERAN/MUGEEZ {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> as well as [[My Type (Saweetie song)|My Type]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.amazon.co.uk/albums/B07WSSQ12Z|title=Amazon Music|website=music.amazon.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> by female rapper [[Saweetie]].\n\nAlso in 2017,  [[2-Tone Entertainment]] entered into a joint publishing venture with [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]] - one of the first signings was Alastair O'Donnell (AoD)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/alastair-odonnell-mn0003440590|title=Alastair O'Donnell {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>, a talented guitarist, songwriter and producer who has had notable success on hit singles including [[WSTRN]] \"[[In2 (song)|In 2]]\" and [[Not3s]] \"[[My Lover (Not3s song)|My Lover]]\". He also had a number of key album tracks on the [[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonce]] ''[[The Lion King (2019 soundtrack)|The Lion King]]'' album, the [[Stormzy]] - \"[[Heavy Is the Head (album)|HITH]]\" album and the [[J Hus]] \"[[Big Conspiracy]]\" [[album]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trenchtrenchtrench.com/news/stormzys-monumental-new-album-heavy-is-the-head-has-arrived|title=Stormzy's Monumental New Album 'Heavy Is The Head' Has Arrived|website=trenchtrenchtrench.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>.\n\nIn February 2020, [[2-Tone Entertainment|2Tone Entertainment]] management client '''Eyelar''' co-wrote the new single for [[Demi Lovato]] titled \"[[Anyone (Demi Lovato song)|Anyone]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/demi-lovatos-anyone-wasnt-written-as-a-comeback-songwriter-eyelar-says-21769205|title=Demi Lovato's \"Anyone\" Wasn't Always A Comeback Song, Songwriter Eyelar Says|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\". The track was premiered at the [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] at the [[Staples Center]] in [[Los Angeles]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsbreak.com/news/0NvAQ5X1/demi-lovatos-2020-grammys-performance-will-feature-song-written-right-before-overdose|title=Demi Lovato's 2020 Grammys Performance Will Feature Song Written Right Before Overdose|website=News Break|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>.\n\nIn March 2020, 2-Tone Entertainment announced via Instagram a new publishing joint venture with '''Stellar Songs'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/label/358627-Stellar-Songs-Ltd|title=Stellar Songs Ltd.|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>- a publishing company who's songwriters include [[Sam Smith]], [[Emeli Sand\u00e9|Emeli Sande]], [[Charli XCX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-PHhb6nEOl/|title=2-Tone Entertainment (2TE)\u2019s Instagram profile post: \u201cRaise a glass \ud83e\udd42- It\u2019s my birthday and also a great opportunity to announce our publishing collaboration with @stellarsongsltd Thank you to\u2026\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Record labels based in London]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2004]]\n", "text_old": "{{Proposed deletion/dated\n  |concern = Blatantly promotional article, substantially written by SPAs. Refbombed, but almost none of the refs are RSes actually about the company. [[WP:BEFORE]] doesn't show much better.\n  |timestamp = 20200331201922\n  |help = off\n}}\n{{advert|date=March 2020}}\n{{puffery|date=March 2020}}\n{{notability|corp|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = 2-Tone Entertainment\n| logo = 2-Tone_Entertainment_Logo_2014.png\n| type = [[Private ownership]],<br>[[Private company]]\n| foundation = 2004\n| founder = Shaurav D'Silva\n| location_city = [[London]]\n| location_country = United Kingdom\n| genre = [[Dance Music]], [[Hip hop music|Hip-hop]], [[Alternative hip hop]], [[R&B]], [[Drum & Bass]], [[Grime (music)|Grime]]\n| area_served = [[United Kingdom]]<br>[[European Union]]\n| key_people = Shaurav D'Silva<br/> <small> (CEO)</small>\n| industry = [[Music industry]],<br> [[Record Label]] <br> [[A&R]] & [[Artist Management]]\n| products = [[Record Label]] <br> [[Publishing]]<br> [[Artist Management]]\n| homepage = {{url|http://www.2tone-entertainment.com}}\n}}\n'''2-Tone Entertainment (also known as 2TE)''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] based [[independent record label|independent Record Label]] who also specialise in Music Publishing and Talent Management.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2tone-entertainment.com |title=Talent Management &#124; A&R Consultancy &#124; Marketing Consultancy |publisher=2-Tone Entertainment |date= |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> The company was founded by Shaurav D'Silva in 2004.\n \n[[2-Tone Entertainment]] have worked with various [[Major Label|major label]] partners including [[Warner Music Group]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/shaurav-dsilva-launches-new-label-warner-bros-records-uk/|title=Shaurav D'Silva launches new imprint with Warner Bros Records UK|date=2016-09-08|website=Music Business Worldwide|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>, [[3 Beat Records]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/d-silva-keeps-the-beat_17682951|title=Jamaica Observer Limited|website=Jamaica Observer|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> & the [[Universal Music Group]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amsterdam-dance-event.nl/en/artists-speakers/shaurav-dsilva/9930/|title=Shaurav D'Silva|website=ADE|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> since 2011, successfully launching the careers of a number of artists including [[Rudimental]], [[Sigma (group)]], [[Fuse ODG]] ,[[Taio Cruz]] and [[Saweetie]].\n\n[[2-Tone Entertainment|2-Tone Entertainment's]] management and publishing roster also represent a number of writers, producers and artists including [[Diztortion]], Alastair O'Donnell (AoD), [[Eyelar]] and [[Ts7|TS7]]. They have also consulted for a number of urban entertainment and lifestyle brands such as [[SBTV]] and [[MOBO]].\n\nOn September 8, 2016, [[Warner Music]] announced the launch of new record label imprint in conjunction with [[2-Tone Entertainment]] called 2TE Records. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicweek.com/labels/read/shaurav-d-silva-to-head-up-new-warner-imprint-2te-records/065901|title=Shaurav D'Silva to head up new Warner imprint 2TE Records|website=Musicweek.com}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe company was founded by Shaurav D'Silva in 2004. His background as a [[UK garage|UK Garage]] DJ and club promoter <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/D-Silva-keeps-the-BEAT_17682951 |title=D'Silva keeps the BEAT - Entertainment |website=JamaicaObserver.com |date=2014-10-05 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> led to him becoming a consultant on a range of urban and dance music related events and projects including the [[Urban Music Awards]] Ceremony,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=15599&sectioncode=1 |title=In The City panel details announced |publisher=Music Week |date=2005-09-23 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> where he brokered deals with lifestyle brands and record companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://urbanmusicawards.net/2011/08/past-winners-2004/ |title=Past winners 2004 |publisher=Urban Music Awards |date= |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==2005-2009==\nThe company began to work more closely with artists and record labels in tastemaker A&R, Promotion and PR. Some of the notable projects included [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]], [[Jazmine Sullivan|Jasmine Sullivan]], [[Taio Cruz]], [[Ginuwine]], [[Joe (singer)|Joe]], [[N-Dubz]] and [[Jay Sean]].\n\nThe company also started to explore international territories, brokering its first deals in the [[Middle East]] and in [[Japan]] with British Lebanese artist Ramzi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubaichronicle.com/2011/05/11/ramzi-launching-new-album-in-dubai/ |title=Dubai ChronicleRamzi launching new album in Dubai |publisher=Dubaichronicle.com |date=2011-05-11 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> Ramzi achieved \"Gold\" Sales status in the [[Middle East]] on the debut album \"Chapter One\" via EMI Records Arabia.\n\n==2010-2011==\nIn 2010, [[2-Tone Entertainment]] released a compilation via [[Ministry of Sound]] Recordings called \"Ayia Napa Reunion 2010\"- which was mixed by [[DJ Cameo]]- it was a mixture of [[UK garage|UK Garage]], [[Funky house|Funky House]] and Commercial Club Tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/ayia-napa-reunion-2010-mixed/id396783049 |title=iTunes - Music - Ayia Napa Reunion 2010 (Mixed by DJ Cameo) by DJ Cameo |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2010-10-10 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ministryofsound.com/shop/product/music/28717/dj-cameo-presents-ayia-napa-reunion-2010/ |title=DJ Cameo Presents Ayia Napa Reunion 2010 |publisher=Ministry of Sound |date=2010-10-10 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> It was accompanied by an online documentary on [[Ayia Napa]] and club culture. A UK tour with [[BBC Radio 1Xtra|BBC 1Xtra]] DJ- [[DJ Cameo]] and [[Paradigm Talent Agency|Coda Talent]] agency followed.\n\n==2011-2012==\n2011 saw [[2-Tone Entertainment]] venture into [[music publisher (popular music)|music publishing]]. Specialising in the development of writers and producers, the team signed female writer and rapper [[Baby Blue (rapper)|Baby Blue]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.district6.co.uk/index.php?page=writers&id=1064 |title=Baby Blue &#124; District 6 &#124; Music Publishing |publisher=District 6 |date= |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> and production outfit [[Rudimental]] through a joint venture with independent [[music publisher (popular music)|music publisher]] District 6 .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.district6.co.uk/index.php?page=writers&id=1079 |title=Piers Agget (Rudimental) &#124; District 6 &#124; Music Publishing |publisher=District 6 |date= |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref>\n\nThe company also begun representing Singer and Film and TV Actress [[Preeya Kalidas]], who released a number of tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01d0jr6 |title=BBC Radio 1 - Nihal, Preeya Kalidas, DaVinche & TazZz All Live On The Show |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2012-03-14 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> Preeya won best female at the Asian Music Awards the same year following her success with the chart single \"[[Cross My Heart (Skepta song)|Cross My Heart]]\" with [[Skepta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storyCode=1044557&sectioncode=1 |title=Jay Sean and Preeya Kalidas win at UK Asian Music Awards |publisher=Music Week |date=2011-03-14 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/cross-my-heart-ft.-preeya/id394940012 |title=iTunes - Music - Cross My Heart (ft. Preeya Kalidas) by Skepta |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2010-10-17 |accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, [[2-Tone Entertainment]] officially begun its relationship with [[3 Beat Records]], a Liverpool Based record label that is part of [[Universal Music Group|Universal Records]].\n\nThe company's role would be to act as A&R Consultants specialising in Urban and Dance music as well as to continue to nurture and develop talent through [[3 Beat Records]] existing label frame work- key projects would include, [[Skepta]], [[Sway (rapper)|Sway]] and [[Matrix & Futurebound]]. One of the first of the first releases under the deal was a collaboration between [[Matrix and Futurebound]] and Luke Bingham for the chart hit, \"[[All I Know (Matrix & Futurebound song)|All I Know]]\".\n\nIn December 2011, the company successfully planned and delivered the 1st annual [[SB.TV|SBTV]] Christmas party, with artists including: [[Labrinth]], [[Devlin (rapper)|Devlin]], [[Rizzle Kicks]], [[Tinchy Stryder]], [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]], [[Misha B]], [[Cher Lloyd]], [[Maxsta]], [[Dot Rotten]] and many others.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matilda Egere-Cooper |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/sbtv-xmas-party-koko-london-6280485.html |title=SB.TV Xmas party, Koko, London - Reviews - Music |publisher=The Independent |date=2011-12-22 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref> The event received critical acclaim and was well attended, reaching capacity. The success of the event led to a number of new event ventures being offered to the company for 2012.\n\n==2012-2013==\nIn February 2012, it was announced that [[2-Tone Entertainment]] would be producing and event managing the annual [[MOBO Awards|Mobo]] Tour, in particular, the event based in Liverpool. The company already had a Liverpool base, following the new formed relationship with Liverpool-based [[3 Beat Records]]. They successfully put on the [[MOBO]] Industry takeover event and showcased a host of exciting new talent from the Liverpool region with the promise of developing more Liverpool based acts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.connexionslive.com/Libraries/Parent_Carers_Documents/MOBO_Tour_2012_-_Liverpool.sflb.ashx |title=The MOBO Tour 2012 |website=Connexionslive.com |accessdate=2014-07-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140311062406/http://www.connexionslive.com/Libraries/Parent_Carers_Documents/MOBO_Tour_2012_-_Liverpool.sflb.ashx |archive-date=2014-03-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The first of those signings was a 13-year-old Liverpool-born singer/songwriter named Tay\u00e1 who was later launched in 2015 after three years of intensive development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://notion.online/|title=Notion - A space for pioneering talent|website=Notion.online}}</ref>\n\n2012 was also the year that UK production outfit [[Rudimental]] had their breakthrough hit \"[[Feel the Love (Rudimental song)|Feel the Love]]\", which was recorded during their deal with [[2-Tone Entertainment]]. The record went on to sell over 1 million copies and became a huge global success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20120603/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 &#124; Official Charts Company|website=Officialcharts.com}}</ref>\n\n==2013-2014==\n2013 saw the successful breakthrough of new signing [[Stylo G]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressparty.com/pg/newsdesk/rachelwhitepr/view/68552/ |title=Stylo G unveils first single on 3 Beat Records - 'Soundbwoy' |publisher=Pressparty |date= |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref> who had chart success with his debut single on the label with \"[[Soundbwoy]]\". The track entered the chart at number 18 on the OCC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2013-06-08/ |title=2013-06-08 Top 40 Official Singles Chart UK Archive |publisher=Official Charts |date=2013-06-08 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref> The track was produced by Dutch born producer [[Diztortion]] who had recently joined the [[2-Tone Entertainment]] Talent Management roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Sweet-sound-of-Diztortion_17544861|title=Sweet sound of Diztortion - Entertainment|first=Jamaica Observer|last=Limited|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe success with [[Stylo G]] was quickly followed by the success of another signing [[Fuse ODG]] with his popular club anthem \"[[Antenna (song)|Antenna]]\" which entered the UK Chart at Number 7 and went on to become a 200,000 plus selling, silver certified record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2013-06-15/ |title=2013-06-15 Top 40 Official Singles Chart UK Archive |publisher=Official Charts |date=2013-06-15 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref>\n\n[[Fuse ODG]] followed \"[[Antenna (song)|Antenna]]\" with \"[[Azonto (Fuse ODG song)|Azonto]]\", a popular dance that was created in [[Ghana]]. The record reached number 29 in the UK OCC Charts.\n\nThe [[MOBO Awards]] recognised the successes of both [[Stylo G]] and [[Fuse ODG]] with 5 nominations at the 2013 Awards. [[Fuse ODG]] went on to win \"Best African Act\".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/interview-mobo-nominee-and-confirmed-artist-afrobeats-superstar-fuse-odg |title=Interview: Mobo Nominee Afrobeats Superstar Fuse Odg &#124; Mobo Awards |publisher=Mobo.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mobo.com/news-blogs/winner-best-african-act-fuse-odg-wows-mobo-fans-million-pound-girl |title=Winner Of 'Best African Act' Fuse ODG Wows MOBO Fans With 'Million Po &#124; MOBO Awards |publisher=Mobo.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the company also signed drum & bass duo [[Sigma (group)|Sigma]]. The first official release on [[3Beat Records]] was the club anthem, \"[[Rudeboy (Sigma song)|Rudeboy]]\"; the track was B-listed on BBC Radio 1 and reached number 56 in the OCC chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/rudeboy-feat.-doctor-single/id742129844 |title=iTunes - Music - Rudeboy (feat. Doctor) - Single by Sigma |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2013-12-15 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref>\n\n==2014-2015==\n[[2-Tone Entertainment]] started 2014 with more cross over chart success with top 10 chart hits for [[Fuse ODG]] with \"[[Million Pound Girl (Badder Than Bad)]]\" and [[Matrix & Futurebound]] with \"[[Control (Matrix & Futurebound song)|Control]]\".\n\nIn April 2014, [[2-Tone Entertainment]] celebrated an [[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]] (OCC) UK Number 1 with [[Sigma (group)]] [[Nobody to Love]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lane |first=Dan |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sigma-score-debut-number-1-single-with-nobody-to-love-2920/ |title=Sigma score debut Number 1 single with Nobody To Love |website=Officialcharts.com |date=2014-04-13 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> The track went on to become a number 1 across 8 countries worldwide and is certified platinum in the UK and New Zealand <ref>[[Nobody to Love]]</ref>\n\n[[Fuse ODG]] followed up his success on \"[[Million Pound Girl (Badder Than Bad)]]\" with a collaboration with Dancehall superstar (Sean_Paul) called \"Dangerous Love\" - this went on to be Fuse's biggest selling solo single (over 400,000 units) and reached UK Number 3 in the UK OCC Charts.\n\nMeanwhile, [[Sigma (group)|Sigma]] released \"[[Changing (Sigma song)|Changing]]\" featuring vocalist Paloma Faith. The record was an instant success and became the band's second Platinum selling Number 1 record in 2014- it was the 1st time an Electronic artist had achieved back to back UK No 1 Records.<ref>{{cite web|last=Copsey |first=Rob |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sigma-land-second-number-1-single-this-year-with-changing-ft-paloma-faith3140/ |title=Sigma land second Number 1 single this year with Changing FT Paloma Faith |website=Officialcharts.com |date=2014-09-21 |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==2015-2016==\nThe venture with [[3 Beat Records|3Beat]] continued to procure chart success with acts that were considered by many to be specialist or underground artists. Both [[Fuse ODG]] and [[Sigma (group)|Sigma]] went on to release albums and achieve continued success both nationally and internationally. The company continued to maintain a policy of signing artists who had a cultural identity and honestly represented credible Urban and Dance music culture.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/D-Silva-keeps-the-BEAT_17682951|title=D'Silva keeps the BEAT - Entertainment|newspaper=[[Jamaica Observer]]}}</ref>\n\n2015 also saw management client [[Diztortion]] have more chart success with the track [[Fester Skank]] which he produced/ featured on for UK Grime Artist [[Lethal Bizzle]]. The track has achieved Gold sales status quickly and became a cult club track.\n\nFollowing the sustained success with [[Sigma (group)|Sigma]] and [[Fuse ODG]], Shaurav D'Silva was nominated for A&R Award Of The Year at the [[Music Week]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweekawards.com/finalists/|title=Home: Music Week Awards 2017|website=Musicweekawards.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Sigma (group)|Sigma]] were also nominee for 2 X [[Brit Awards]] - for Best Video and for Best Single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brits.co.uk/news/british-single-nominations-announced|title=British Single nominations announced|website=Brits.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==2016-2020==\n2016 saw [[2-Tone Entertainment]] announcing its new label venture with [[Warner Music]]. 2TE Records was launched in January 2017. In the Press release via Music Business worldwide, Shaurav D'Silva mentioned his desire to create \"global superstars from the world of Urban and Dance music\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/shaurav-dsilva-launches-new-label-warner-bros-records-uk/|title=Shaurav D'Silva launches new imprint with Warner Bros Records UK|date=September 8, 2016|website=Musicbusinessworldwide.com}}</ref> The venture saw the label sign a number of artists including US Rapper [[Saweetie]] , [[Taio Cruz]] , [[Fuse ODG]] , and [[Disc jockey|Dj]]/ producers Conducta, and Crazy Cousinz. Key releases under the deal included [[Fuse ODG]]'s collaboration with [[Ed Sheeran]] - [[Boa Me]] as well as the global hit [[My Type (Saweetie song)|My Type]] by female rapper [[Saweetie]].\n\nIn 2017,  [[2-Tone Entertainment]] also entered into a joint publishing venture with [[BMG Rights Management|BMG]] - one of the first signings was Alastair O'Donnell (AoD), a talented guitarist, songwriter and producer who has had notable success on hit singles including [[WSTRN]] \"[[In2 (song)|In 2]]\" and [[Not3s]] \"[[My Lover (Not3s song)|My Lover]]\". He also had a number of key album tracks on the [[Beyonc\u00e9|Beyonce]] ''[[The Lion King (2019 soundtrack)|The Lion King]]'' album, the [[Stormzy]] - \"[[Heavy Is the Head (album)|HITH]]\" album and the [[J Hus]] \"[[Big Conspiracy]]\" [[album]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trenchtrenchtrench.com/news/stormzys-monumental-new-album-heavy-is-the-head-has-arrived|title=Stormzy's Monumental New Album 'Heavy Is The Head' Has Arrived|website=trenchtrenchtrench.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>.\n\nIn February 2020, songwriter management client Eyelar co-wrote the new single for [[Demi Lovato]] titled \"[[Anyone (Demi Lovato song)|Anyone]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/demi-lovatos-anyone-wasnt-written-as-a-comeback-songwriter-eyelar-says-21769205|title=Demi Lovato's \"Anyone\" Wasn't Always A Comeback Song, Songwriter Eyelar Says|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\". The track was premiered at the [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] at the [[Staples Center]] in [[Los Angeles]].\n\n==Key Artist/Writer Releases Discography ==\n[[Taio Cruz]]- [[Departure (Taio Cruz album)|Departure]] <br>\n[[Jay Sean]]- [[My Own Way (album)|My Own Way]] <br>\n[[N Dubz]]- [[Uncle B]] <br> \n[[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]]- [[I Am Chipmunk]] <br>\n[[Jazmine Sullivan]]- [[Fearless (Jazmine Sullivan album)|Fearless]] <br>\n[[Ginuwine]]- [[A Man's Thoughts|A Mans Thoughts]] <br>\n[[Mz Bratt]]- Who Do You Think You Are <br>\n[[Rudimental]]- Sexy Sexy <br>\n[[Rudimental]]- Speeding <br>\n[[DJ Cameo|Dj Cameo]]- Ayia Napa Reunion 2010 <br>\n[[Rudimental]]- [[Feel the Love (Rudimental song)|Feel the Love]] <br>\n[[Preeya Kalidas]]- Love Between Us <br>\n[[Baby Blue (rapper)]]- Target <br>\n[[ts7|TS7]] Ft. Taylor Fowlis- [[Heartlight (Polygon)]] <br>\n[[Matrix & Futurebound]] ft Luke Bingham - \"[[All I Know (Matrix & Futurebound song)|All I Know]]\" 